In the equation above, Cm and Cr are the elastic tensors of the matrix and rth inclusion respectively, and fm and fr stand for their respective volume fractions. The fourth-order tensors Am and Ar are strain concentration tensors defined as follows
(9)Am=[vmI+∑r=1Nfr[I+SrCm-1(Cr-Cm)]-1]-1(a)Ar=[I+SrCm-1(Cr-Cm)]-1Am(b)
where I is the fourth-order identity tensor and Sr is the Eshelby tensor of the rth inclusion. In fact, the Eshelby tensor is a function of the matrix property and the aspect ratio of inclusions43 that are taken to be cylindrical here. The elements of the Eshelby tensor for an ellipsoidal inclusion, applicable for cylindrical shape, are as follows.43 In the following equations, α is the aspect ratio of the cylinders and νm is the Poisson’s ratio of the matrix.
(10.a)S1111=12(1-νm){1-2νm+3α2-1α2-1   -[1-2νm+3α2α2-1]q}
(10.b)S2222=S3333=38(1-νm)α2α2-1   +14(1-νm)[1-2νm+94(α2-1)]q
(10.c)S2233=S3322=14(1-νm){α2α2-1   -[1-2νm+34(α2-1)]q}
(10.d)S2211=S3311=-12(1-νm)α2α2-1   +14(1-νm){3α2α2-1-1+2νm}q
(10.e)S1122=S1133=-12(1-νm)[1-2νm+1α2-1]   +12(1-νm)[1-2νm+32(α2-1)]q
(10.f)S2323=S3232=14(1-νm){α22(α2-1)   +[1-2νm-34(α2-1)]q}
(10.g)S1212=S1313=14(1-νm){1-2νm-α2+1α2-1   -12[1-2νm-3(α2+1)α2-1]q}
(10.h)q=α(α2-1)3/2{α(α2-1)1/2-cosh-1α}
